5 minute no cook play dough? Yes please! And with just 4 simple ingredients! Even better…

Mix:
2 cups of white flour, 
0.5 cup of salt, 
2 tbsp cream of tartar

Add 2 tbsp of any neutral oil - I use coconut oil. 

Add 1.5 boiling hot water - be careful and make sure the kids are far away as this can be dangerous. 

Mix until dough forms - add more flour if it’s still sticky, but mix well before you add more. 

Done!! You can separate it out and add food colouring. Secret to vibrant colours? Gel food colouring!! 

Keeps for a few months in a zip lock bag :)

What is bilateral coordination? Bilateral means “both sides.” Bilateral coordination is using both sides of the body together in an activity. Playing music is scientifically proven to increase the part of the brain that connects the two hemispheres by 25%!! For toddlers, threading, braiding, beading all are great at improving this coordination ❤️ #montessori #toddler #brain #music

Study by neurologist and neuroscientist Gottfried Schlaug  and team detailed magnetic resonance images of the children’s brains at age 6 and again at 9. Children who practiced at least 2.5 hours a week in the time between the scans, revealed that the corpus callosum grew by 25% growth compared children who averaged only an hour or two of weekly practice and those who dropped their instruments entirely showed no such growth. All of the children practiced instruments, such as a piano or a violin, that required two hands. Starting coordination activities early such as threading, beading, braiding is a great way to kick start coordination needed to start music :)

Why teach analogue since digital is everywhere…well 

1. analog clocks help children understand that subtraction is not just “taking away”, it is also “the difference between two numbers.”

2. Analog clocks give children more practice with multiple names for the same quantity.  Knowing that “2:40” and “twenty to 3:00” refer to the same time helps build on the important big idea of equivalence.

3. Skip counting is the natural precursor to multiplication, and counting by fives is a natural skill that has a useful context when telling time.

4. “Clock arithmetic” is a number system that is not base 10.  Time builds an appreciation for twelves and sixties.  These are both really important numbers that have many factors and 12 can be divided evenly by 2,3,4,6 and 12, and the number 60 is also divisible by 5, 10, 15, 30! #montessori #toddler #baby #clock #math

Traveling with young kids can be intimidating! Especially on long flights where you need to keep them occupied. 

#ad We received two of these @educatingamy activity books and they were such an incredible option for the kids.

It was nice to have something that wasn't just more screen time! While we aren't personally opposed to a little screen time here and there, we didn't want it to be the entire 6 hour flight.

These books were great for the airport when our flight was delayed as well as during the flight. Even our 16-month-old son really enjoyed the books. We had two and switched between the three kids who got to use them at any given time. It was especially helpful with our 1-year-old who we don't do screen time with. He truly enjoyed using these and it was nice to you see the excitement with each page. 

Not only are they fun, they actually teach different skills which is awesome! My girls really loved the page for them to play doctor with the little felt doll and the home care page. It allowed them to dress up the dolls and wash and iron the clothing. They thought that was a lot of fun.

My son really loved the buckle pages. He loves putting buckles together right now and enjoyed doing that and number of different times. I'm pretty sure he would have been happy to do that for an hour straight!

Children are perfectly capable of cleaning up after themselves, so why do parents do it for them? Often, we think if we do it ourselves, it will be done faster (and better.) It is often much easier to just clean up than to guide and remind kids about cleaning. The problem is it doesn’t teach our children anything. Asking children to tidy up after themselves gives them discipline, skills, and a sense of responsibility and pride. These qualities will be useful as they grow older and become “messy” teenagers; they’ll be much more likely to keep their things tidy if they’ve always had the responsibility to do so. #montessori #baby #chores #toddler #toddlersofinstagram

As someone who shied away from attention during my own childhood, watching my child’s carefree spirit was a heartwarming and beautiful experience, free from the burden of worrying about what others might think.

These precious moments are crucial in shaping her self-confidence and nurturing her authentic selves. As a parent, my greatest wish is for my daughter to understand that it’s perfectly okay to be loud and take up space and that she doesn’t need to conform to anyone else’s expectations.

By allowing her to be herself, I believe we are laying the foundation for a strong sense of individuality and self-worth. It’s through these small acts of support and encouragement that our children can grow up knowing that they are loved and accepted for who they truly are.

As we journey through parenthood together, I am determined to protect her right to be herself and to embrace her uniqueness. It’s not just about letting her sparkle during bike rides; it’s about empowering her to shine throughout her entire life. I will stand proudly beside her, providing unwavering support as she navigates her path.

In a world that pressures us to conform, especially girls, I hope my daughter will always remember the freedom and happiness she felt today, riding her bike in that sparkly dress. It’s a powerful reminder that being true to oneself is a beautiful and empowering way to live life.

#EmbraceAuthenticity #LetThemSparkle #parentingjourney #toddler #daughter

Phonemic awareness is the foundational skill that allows kids to understand and manipulate the smallest units of sound in spoken language, known as phonemes. These are the distinct sounds that make up words, like the “buh” sound in “bat” or the “kuh” sound in “cat.”

Having strong phonemic awareness means being able to recognize, isolate, blend, and segment these phonemes in words. It’s a critical skill for early literacy development because it forms the basis for decoding words when reading and encoding them when writing.

When children have a good grasp of phonemic awareness, they are better equipped to sound out unfamiliar words, spell more accurately, and develop strong reading and writing skills. It’s like the essential building block upon which their literacy abilities are constructed, making it a fundamental skill in the journey towards becoming proficient readers and writers. #toddler #montessori #literacy #earlyliteracy

🌟 The Key to Toddler Independence: Montessori Teacher’s Top Tip! 🧒💪

My number one tip for fostering independence in toddlers is taking the time to show them how to do things for themselves. It might seem like it takes longer in the beginning, but it pays off in the long run.

By patiently demonstrating tasks and involving them in daily activities, you empower toddlers to develop essential life skills and build confidence. This hands-on approach helps them become more self-reliant and capable individuals as they grow.

Remember, the journey to independence is a gradual process, and your guidance and support play a crucial role. 🌱🌟 #MontessoriParenting #IndependenceInToddlers #childdevelopment

🚽 Beginning the Potty Training Journey: Montessori Teacher’s Top Tips! 🧒💺

Starting toilet training can be an exciting adventure for both you and your child. Here’s how to kick off the journey:

Readiness Assessment: Assess your child’s readiness by looking for signs like showing interest, staying dry for longer, or attempting to remove their diaper.
Introduce the Potty: Familiarize your child with the potty, let them sit on it fully clothed, and make it a part of their daily routine.
Potty Talk: Use positive language and explain the purpose of the potty. Encourage them to communicate when they need to go.
Consistency: Create a consistent schedule for potty breaks, especially after meals and naps.
Celebrate Small Wins: Praise and celebrate every success, no matter how small.
Remember, every child progresses at their own pace, so be patient and provide plenty of encouragement. 🚽 Navigating Regression in Toilet Learning: Montessori Teacher’s Guidance! 🧒💔

It’s not uncommon for children to experience setbacks in toilet training. Here’s how to manage regression:

Stay Calm: Keep your cool and avoid showing frustration. Regression is a natural part of the process.
Reassure and Encourage: Provide reassurance that accidents happen and that it’s okay. Encourage them to try again next time.
Review Routine: Check if there have been any changes in their routine or environment that might be causing stress.
Offer Independence: Allow them to take the lead when they’re ready. Offer support but avoid pressure.

Remember, each child’s journey is unique, and setbacks are a part of the learning process.

Respect: Treat diaper changes as a routine part of caring for your child, showing respect for their comfort and needs.

⭐️MORE TIPS for successful quiet time:

🛏️Establish a quiet time routine: Having a consistent routine will help your toddler understand and anticipate when it's time for quiet activities.

🤫Set clear expectations: Explain to your toddler what quiet time is and what is expected of them during this period. Use simple and age-appropriate language to help them understand that it's a time for calmness and relaxation.

🧘‍♀️Encourage relaxation skills: Help your toddler develop regulation skills for when they feel restless or fidgety during quiet time. This can include deep breathing exercises or gentle stretching.

⏰Be patient: It may take some time for your toddler to adjust to quiet time, especially if they're used to more active play. Be patient and supportive during this transition, and remember that it's a learning process for them.
